nments. What follows are detailed assessments and recommendations for each value chain that outline critical steps for success in the sectors, along with overall suggestions for boosting coastal economies and supporting pilots for farmer programs. Important to note is the ever-present threat of climate change, as each of the selected value chains will be affected by rising sea temperatures and more turbulent waters. These efforts are expected to contribute to a holistic approach for ensuring sustainable, meaningful impact, both for Kenyan ecosystems and for local-ar- ea alternative livelihoods. Acknowledgements xii Blue entrepreneurship scoping study in Kenya Acknowledgements We thank key IUCN contributors to the research effort: James Oliver and Francis Okalo. We thank Sida for the funding that made this scoping study possible. We thank supporting partners (St\u00e9phanie Canac and Alexis Grosskopf from OceanHub Africa, along with Fennie Lansbergen from Enviu) for their research contributions and supportive discussions. We thank Dan Odiwuor and Norah Magangi from KMFRI (Kenya Marine and Fisheries Research Institute) for their support and efforts toward data collection in the field. We also acknowledge the significant and invaluable contributions of a wide panel of stakeholders who donated time and thoughtful insight that shaped the direction and content of the research. A full list of organizations and individuals who shared information for the report can be found in Appendix 1: Stakeholder Interviews. List of acronyms xiii Blue entrepreneurship scoping study in Kenya List of acronyms CAGR compound annual growth rate CWiFE Coastal Women in Fisheries Entrepreneurship EEZ Exclusive Economic Zone EIA Environmental Impact Assessment FAO Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations GDP gross domestic product IMTA integrated multi-trophic aquaculture IUCN International Union for Conservation of Nature IUU Illegal, Unregulated and Unreported JKP Jumuiy aya Kaun