rine-based incomes, while also promoting sustainable, regenerative value propositions that actively protect and enhance the ocean environment. Fortunately, Kenyan president Uhuru Kenyatta has marked2 the Blue Economy as an integral driver for reaching", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9c2a5c4a-01ed-49db-be5b-1399ffb25116": {"__data__": {"id_": "9c2a5c4a-01ed-49db-be5b-1399ffb25116", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/deep-sea-atlas-eastern-mediterranean", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Deep-sea Atlas of the Eastern Mediterranean", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/deep-sea-atlas-eastern-mediterranean", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "13abc4f2146bfef904a2b6be0c4b857a07d9beadd08680ff60c987003dd1d189"}, "3": {"node_id": "9b82a291-5c90-4270-a6db-8f3e6f6befd8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/deep-sea-atlas-eastern-mediterranean", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c973c4c7290b4f77a5f478cc0eb0f46f3c7545ae8a9d97a0f5246df31e970929"}}, "hash": "557e15d41ab4e6d8109782d4500a3945dd34097faa13f23c595ad7aa25aef24c", "text": "Kenya\u2019s \u2018Vision 2030,\u2019 Kenya\u2019s \u201clong-term development blueprint for the country.\u201d3 As the nation and its priorities reflect the importance of sustainably capitalizing on the economic potential along Kenya\u2019s coast and water- ways, IUCN can expect to seamlessly offer support to government strategies by finding ways to promote and grow markets in the Blue Entrepreneurship space. Furthermore, Kenya sits among the 14 countries on the High Level Panel for a Sustainable Ocean Economy (Ocean Panel),4 an initiative which further highlights Kenya\u2019s enthusiasm for identifying innovative solutions that will protect the ocean and develop ocean-based economic opportunities. Not only does Kenya\u2019s participation in the groundbreaking Ocean Panel reinforce the degree to which the national government is primed to en- gage in this space, but the Ocean Panel itself serves as a resource for cutting-edge technologies and captivating ideas, and it acts as a global support for sustainable Blue Economy ventures. Looking at the potential support for entre- preneurship, Kenya shows immense prom- ise around innovation and new ventures, as evidenced by the World Economic Forum flagging Kenya as an \u201cemerging global start- up hotspot.\u201d5 Kenya is actively prioritizing startup ventures through its Enterprise Kenya program, the government\u2019s \u201cnational accelerator to catalyse innovations and pro- vide entrepreneurs with needed support in Introduction 2 Blue entrepreneurship scoping study in Kenya their innovation journey.\u201d6 Additionally, the amount of funding toward startups and the number of investments shows a continued increase from previous years, with Kenya benefitting from US$564 million in invest- ment funding in 2019, ranked second across the African continent behind Nigeria only.7 While still battling some of the challenges common to lower middle-income econo- mies, Kenya showcases that its startup envi- ronment is conducive and can be expected to grow ocean ventures. The potential to drive impact among coastal communities grows year-on-year, as a combination of factors highlights Blue Entrepreneurship as a key driver. For example, global demand for ocean-based and ocean-adjacent products and services continues to grow, due to a rising global population8 who need inexpensive protein sources,9,10 an increasing middle-class inter- ested in travel,11 and a growing proportion of world tourism being dedicated to \u201cemerging markets.\u201d12 Kenya benefits from both of these sectors, with 0.8%13 of national gross domes- tic product (GDP) dedicated to fisheries and 6 ICT Authority. (n.d.). Enterprise Kenya. https://icta.go.ke/enterprise-kenya/ 7 Partech Africa. (2020). 2019 Africa Tech Venture Capital Report. https://cdn-website.partechpartners.com/media/ documents/2020.01_Partech_Africa_-_2019_Africa_Tech_VC_Report_FINAL.pdf 8 United Nations (UN). (n.d.). Global Issues: Population. https://www.un.org/en/global-issues/population 9 The World Bank Group, Agriculture And Environmental Services. (2013). Fish to 2030: Prospects for Fisheries and Aquaculture. pp.44-45. http://www.fao.org/3/i3640e/i3640e.pdf 10 Moskowitz, P. (2014, May 19). U.N.: Record-high global demand for fish threatens oceans. Aljazeera America. http://america. aljazeera.com/articles/2014/5/19/aquaculture-fishingreport.html 11 WTTC (World Travel & Tourism Council). (2020). Travel & Tourism: Global Economic Impact & Trends 2020. p.3. https://wttc.org/ Portals/0/Documents/Reports/2020/Global%20Economic%20Impact%20Trends%202020.pdf?ver=2021-02-25-183118-360 12 Sign\u00e9, L., Johnson, C. (2018). Africa\u2019s tourism potential: Trends, drivers, opportunities, and strategies. p.5. Brookings. https://www. brookings.edu/research/africas-tourism-potential/ 13 KMFRI (Kenya Marine And Fisheries Research Institute). (2017). Kenya\u2019s Aquaculture Brief 2017: Status, Trends, Challenges and Future Outlook.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9b82a291-5c90-4270-a6db-8f3e6f6befd8": 